Linear Regression Model (Base Model)¶

To better understand escooter usage in Chicago over the program period a linear regression base model will be established to compare the performance of alternate machine learning models.

The model will consider independent variables from alternate data sources including weather data, taxi trip data, traffic accident data and public transport data to predict number of escooter trips. The justification for the inclusion of these data sources was the availability of the data and the logical impact that these variables may have on the number of escooter trips taken.

The regression model should provide insight into what factors contribute to the number of escooter trips (the dependent variable).

Import Data¶

The following data sources were imported and merged to create the data set:

  • The E-ScooterTrips-_2020 data set that contains trip data collected during the trial.
  • The TaxiTrips-_2020.csv data set that contains taxi trip data for Chicago
  • The CTA_-Ridership-_Daily_Boarding_Totals dataset shows boardings for both bus and rail service in Chicago
  • The Traffic Crashes - Vehicles data set contains information about vehicles involved in a traffic crash in Chicago
  • The Chicago Weather Observations Data dataset contains observed weather conditions in Chicago during the course of the trial.

Regression Model (Numerical Variables Only)¶

Firstly a regression model fitting only the numerical variables will be fitted and performance evaluated. The data will first be split into training and testing data.

#fitting the model and predicting on test data
linreg = LinearRegression()
linreg.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred = linreg.predict(X_test)
print ('MAE:', mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred))
print ('MSE:', mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))
print ('RMSE:', np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)))
print ('R2:', r2_score(y_test, y_pred))

MSE: 38903.13853829788

R2: 0.4663275689251728

The RMSE of 197.24 is large relative to the mean which suggests that the model does not perfom well in predicting the hourly number of escooter trips.

The $R^2$ value indicates that the model explains only 46.6% of the variation in the number of escoter trips taken.

Summary¶

Originally 14 variables were assessed for suitability to be included within the model.

A number of variables were dropped from the model as they were considered to be not independent observations, a base assumption of a linear regression model.

From the pair plot no strong linear relationships were evident between the dependent and independent variables. A weak positive linear relationship was observed between escooter trips and temperature and possibly between escooter trips and traffic incidents. A strong positive relationship was observed between bus trips and rail trips. To prevent multicollinearity issues with the model, the number of rail trips variable was removed.

A correlation heatmap reinforced the existence of a weak positive relationship between escooter trips and temperature, and escooter trips and total traffic incidents. The positive relationship with escooter and temperature makes sense as traveling by escooter is an outdoor activity, logically the weather would make an impact on a users decision to travel by escooter. Interestingly there was no correlation observed between precipitation and escooter trips. The correlation between escooter trips and traffic incidents may be due to a confounding variable such as more people traveling.

The categorical variables, month, day and time were analysed and it was observed that these categorical variables could have a significant effect on the prediction of escooter trips. This was reinforced by the improved performance of the model with both numerical and categorical variables compared to the model with only numerical variables.

The first model run included only the numerical variables. The RMSE of the model was 197.24 which is relatively large in comparison to the mean. 46.6% of the variation in escooter trips is explained by the model. This model performs poorly in predicting the hourly number of escooter trips.

In an attempt to increase performance, categorical variables were converted to dummy variables and added to the model. This significantly improves the model performance with the $R^2$ value increasing 69.96%. The RMSE also improves to 153.89, however this is still large relative to the mean. The coefficients of the models variables show that time of day, day of the week and month have a significant influence in predicting escooter trips. Of the numerical variables temperature was one of the better predictors of escooter trips. Overall the linear regression model was able to predict the hourly number of escooter trips with reasonable accuracy.
